---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'

const packages = [
  {
    name: 'Spectre Tokens',
    detail:
      'Foundation-level values for color, spacing, type, surfaces, and motion decisions.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Spectre UI',
    detail:
      'Shared UI primitives and styling contracts that keep implementation aligned across products.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Spectre UI Astro',
    detail:
      'Astro-friendly bindings for teams shipping fast sites and application surfaces with the same system core.',
  },
]
---

<Layout
  title="Spectre Design"
  description="Spectre Design covers Spectre Tokens, Spectre UI, and Spectre UI Astro."
>
  <section class="page-intro">
    <p class="eyebrow">Spectre Design</p>
    <h1 class="display-headline">Design foundations built for real product delivery.</h1>
    <p class="lead page-lead">
      Spectre Design defines the visual language once, then makes it usable from
      tokens to UI code to Astro implementation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section-block">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Packages</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">One design system, three implementation layers.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="stack-list">
      {
        packages.map((item) => (
          <article class="stack-item">
            <p class="stack-item__kicker">Package</p>
            <h3 class="stack-item__title">{item.name}</h3>
            <p class="stack-item__copy">{item.detail}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-block section-band">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why it matters</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Reduce drift between design decisions and shipped code.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="two-column-copy">
      <p>
        Spectre Design is for teams that want stronger alignment between system
        governance and daily implementation. Tokens define the contract. UI
        primitives enforce consistency. Astro support keeps content surfaces on
        the same language.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is a system that scales without becoming vague, ornamental,
        or disconnected from production work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
